Rotational and translational diffusion of protein and lipid
molecules in biological membranes has recently become accessible to experimental study (1-4). The problem can be studied theoretically by applying the classical analysis of Brownian motion to a hydrodynamic model. A simple model is one in which .the membrane is taken as an infinite plane sheet of viscous fluid (lipid) separating infinite regions of less viscous liquid (water). The protein molecule is regarded as a cylinder, with axis perpendicular to the plane of the sheet, moving about in the sheet under the action of Brownian motion (Fig. 1).
