We shall now state the results for these three approaches. It may be kept in mind that although in principle any two or all three effects can be incorporated at the same time, analytical difficulties render this impractical. On the other hand, the methods of calculation imply that the effects add reciprocally (like resistances in parallel), so it is sufficient to treat them separately. Also, these effects are minor corrections for the rotational mobility which is given to sufficient accuracy by Eq. 5.
Eqs. 3, 5, 7, and 8 are obtained by using the traditional boundary condition of no slip on the surface of the particle. Recently doubts have been raised about the universal appropriateness of this boundary condition (8). It has been found that in organic solvents rotational relaxation of small molecules is better described by a boundary condition implying perfect slip (no tangential stress) between solvent and solute, while in aqueous solutions the behavior of small molecules is intermediate, depending on the number of hydrogen bonds formed between solvent and solute (9). In real membranes it is not obvious which condition is appropriate. In our model it turns out that the translational mobility is changed little by the choice of boundary condition, and these changes will be given. The rotational mobility, however, could be very
high for a very symmetrical particle and a slip boundary
condition. For an asymmetric molecule the rotational mobility may be quite similar for "slip" or "stick," but model calculations would be very complicated.

